Yes — this is the right next slice. For this part, I would touch only src/aerolitctl/cli.py, plus one small backend cleanup in server.py so boolean CLI flags do not accidentally reset saved config when omitted.

1. Small server.py cleanup first

This makes CLI booleans safer.

In run_configure_server(...), change these defaults:

configure_interface=False,
nfs_enabled=True,
nfs_allow_all_clients=False,
nfs_create_export_path=False,
firewall_manage=True,

to:

configure_interface=None,
nfs_enabled=None,
nfs_allow_all_clients=None,
nfs_create_export_path=None,
firewall_manage=None,

Then in build_plan_from_values(...), change the same defaults:

configure_interface=False,
nfs_enabled=True,
nfs_allow_all_clients=False,
nfs_create_export_path=False,
firewall_manage=True,

to:

configure_interface=None,
nfs_enabled=None,
nfs_allow_all_clients=None,
nfs_create_export_path=None,
firewall_manage=None,

Then inside build_plan_from_values(...), right after this line:

current_nfs = server.get("nfs", {})

add this:

if configure_interface is None:
    configure_interface = server.get("configure_interface", False)
if nfs_enabled is None:
    nfs_enabled = current_nfs.get("enabled", True)
if nfs_allow_all_clients is None:
    nfs_allow_all_clients = current_nfs.get("allow_all_clients", False)
if nfs_create_export_path is None:
    nfs_create_export_path = current_nfs.get("create_export_path", False)
if firewall_manage is None:
    firewall_manage = server.get("firewall", {}).get("manage", True)

That prevents this kind of problem:

aerolitctl configure server --mode full --interface ens160

from accidentally turning off existing configure_interface, NFS, or firewall choices just because you did not pass every flag again.

